three to four","Weeks four to five","Weeks five to six","Weeks six to seven","Weeks eight to nine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring \u003Cstrong\u003Eweeks five to six\u003C/strong\u003E of embryonic development, primordial germ cells migrate from their origin in the wall of the yolk sac, through the dorsal mesentery of the hindgut, to reach the developing gonadal ridges.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect timing options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeeks three to four\u003C/strong\u003E - Too early, as the germ cells are still developing in the yolk sac wall\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeeks four to five\u003C/strong\u003E - Migration has not yet begun at this stage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeeks six to seven\u003C/strong\u003E - Migration is already complete by this time\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeeks eight to nine\u003C/strong\u003E - Well after migration has finished; cells have already colonised the gonadal ridges\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis migration is guided by specific molecular signals including chemokines. Successful migration is crucial for normal gonad development and fertility. Failed migration can result in infertility or extragonadal germ cell tumours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Primordial germ cells originate in the yolk sac wall and migrate through the dorsal mesentery to reach the developing gonads during weeks 5-6 of embryonic development.","The migration path follows the hindgut mesentery and involves specific molecular signals that guide the cells to their destination.","Successful primordial germ cell migration is essential for normal gonad development and fertility."],"references":["Richardson BE, Lehmann R. Mechanisms guiding primordial germ cell migration: strategies from different organisms. Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol. 2010 Jan;11(1):37-49. doi: 10.1038/nrm2815. PMID: 20027186; PMCID: PMC4521894.","Barton LJ, Roa-de la Cruz L, Lehmann R, Lin B. The journey of a generation: advances and promises in the study of primordial germ cell migration. Development. 2024 Apr 1;151(7):dev201102. doi: 10.1242/dev.201102. Epub 2024 Apr 12. Erratum in: Development. 2024 May 15;151(10):dev203034. doi: 10.1242/dev.203034. PMID: 38607588; PMCID: PMC11165723.","Donovan MF, Arbor TC, Bordoni B. Embryology, Yolk Sac. [Updated 2023 Mar 6]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555965/","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16111"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T21:54:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T21:55:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8802"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74155"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"sel